  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through various mechanisms:\n\n1. International Legal Frameworks\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- International anti-money laundering standards\n\n2. Regulatory Cooperation\n- Information sharing between national financial intelligence units\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Coordinated investigations across jurisdictions\n- Extradition agreements for financial crimes\n\n3. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Cross-border transaction monitoring\n- Consistent risk assessment frameworks\n\n4. Enforcement Strategies\n- Harmonized criminal prosecution approaches\n- Shared databases of suspicious financial activities\n- International sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Collaborative asset seizure and recovery processes\n\n5. Common Legal Principles\n- Criminalization of money laundering\n- Due diligence requirements\n- Transparency in financial transactions\n- Reporting obligations for financial institutions\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multilayered approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering across different legal systems and national boundaries.",
